{
  "doc_id": "53561",
  "text": "Gr-1 + CD11b + cells are deregulated by diabetes and include monocytes, granulocytes, and precursors. They home to injury sites after mobilization from the bone marrow (BM), neutralize pathogens early in healing, and promote angiogenesis later in repair [CITATION_1] . Wound recruitment is controlled by the chemokine receptors CCR2 and CxCR2 [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , which are expressed by Ly6C + monocytes [CITATION_4] and Ly6G + granulocytes [CITATION_5] , respectively. Both subsets are required for timely healing, and CCR2 + monocytes play a crucial role in wound angiogenesis [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . However, diabetes significantly expands the Gr-1 + population in the blood [CITATION_8] and elevated numbers are recruited to and retained in the db wound [CITATION_9] . They show an altered monocyte/granulocyte differentiation capacity, possess aberrant chemotactic and adhesive properties, and fail to promote wound angiogenesis [CITATION_10] . The impact of diabetes on individual Gr-1 + subpopulations is unknown. Chronic inflammation perturbs hematopoiesis, possibly via increased myeloid cell turnover at inflammatory sites and a correspondingly elevated demand [CITATION_11] . Stable intrinsic defects induced in myeloid cells by diabetes prior to wound recruitment promote chronic inflammation and impair healing [CITATION_12] . Persistent Ly6C/Gr-1 and diminished F4.80 expression in the db wound suggest that one facet of the aberrant myeloid cell phenotype is persistent immaturity [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] . It is unknown whether this is prespecified, but peripheral blood myeloid cells from db patients have impaired effector functions, including bacterial killing and phagocytosis, that are characteristic of immaturity [CITATION_15] . Candidate mechanisms underlying intrinsic defects in differentiation include altered histone modifications at gene promoters of important myeloid differentiation genes, as found at inflammatory genes in vitro in response to high glucose [CITATION_16] . However, data from primary cells are limited and the promoters of genes involved in myeloid differentiation remain unexamined.",
